68. Tantalus, etc.: Horace be- gins as though he were going to warn the miser by the story of Tan- talus in the world below, in the manner of a preacher of virtue, a class of men not held in much re· spect. See Sat. II. 3 and I. 1. 120.

But Horace turns upon him, and shows that Tantalus' fate is not a future terror, but his condition now.
